    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I have been double checking this and it's \"on purpose\" that we update the url at every keystroke to provide the right feedback to our users.\n\nThen, the thresold is only the minimum time between two search states where we decide to create a new state.\n\nSo when putting thresold: 10000 (10s) it means that we will create new search states every 10s. The thresold is our way of saying \"After xxxms of inactivity, we consider the state to be one to remember when going back\".\n\nExample with 10s:\n- t0 page load (enpty query)\n- t0+1 type hello (url is updated like h, e, l, l, o\n- t0+8 type mom (url is updated like m, o, m)\n- t0 + 9 click on back button (url is back like at t0 and query is empty)\n\nYou are now back at the initial state because we were not able to create any search state.\n\nI understand this may not be the behavior you might want to build into your application but this is the correct behavior given the implementation.\n\nI will update the documentation on this part.\n\nIf you want to have a different behavior or a new parameter then please open a new issue. Thanks!\n",
    "created_at": "2016-04-28T21:16:15Z",
